00:32:46.992 --> 00:32:49.200
MOLLY KNIGHT RASKIN: Does
anybody have any questions?

00:32:53.182 --> 00:32:54.640
AUDIENCE: I actually
had a question

00:32:54.640 --> 00:32:57.870
about-- I mean, as
best as you can tell,

00:32:57.870 --> 00:33:01.360
was his intent when he
went to graduate school

00:33:01.360 --> 00:33:05.780
at MIT to become an academic,
and then he sort of evolved

00:33:05.780 --> 00:33:08.490
into this entrepreneur
because of his relationship

00:33:08.490 --> 00:33:09.470
with his professor?

00:33:09.470 --> 00:33:12.577
Or was that a driver
all along with him?

00:33:12.577 --> 00:33:14.660
MOLLY KNIGHT RASKIN: That's
such a great question.

00:33:14.660 --> 00:33:17.580
It was never a driver.

00:33:17.580 --> 00:33:21.112
His big dream was to become a
professor like Tom Leighton,

00:33:21.112 --> 00:33:25.700
to get his PhD at
MIT, and to become

00:33:25.700 --> 00:33:28.510
a professor of computer
science and math.

00:33:28.510 --> 00:33:33.530
And he dreamed of going back
to the Technion in Israel.

00:33:33.530 --> 00:33:35.900
In fact, his professor
there really believed

00:33:35.900 --> 00:33:37.370
that he would come
back some day.

00:33:37.370 --> 00:33:40.270
And I think he
probably would have.

00:33:40.270 --> 00:33:42.870
And another wonderful
part of this story

00:33:42.870 --> 00:33:47.220
is that, as I mentioned,
Danny and others

00:33:47.220 --> 00:33:50.720
who were studying
at MIT at the time

00:33:50.720 --> 00:33:54.870
became very rich off
of Akamai's success.

00:33:54.870 --> 00:33:58.350
And I set out as a
journalist sort of thinking,

00:33:58.350 --> 00:34:01.130
oh, come on, really,
that much money?

00:34:01.130 --> 00:34:02.400
It must have changed him.

00:34:02.400 --> 00:34:03.490
It must have.

00:34:03.490 --> 00:34:06.550
And the skeptic in
me really wanted

00:34:06.550 --> 00:34:09.790
to find out what that meant
for him, because, again,

00:34:09.790 --> 00:34:13.389
his dream was absolutely and
squarely to be an academic.

00:34:13.389 --> 00:34:15.810
And he came to
Boston, Cambridge,

00:34:15.810 --> 00:34:19.610
with really no other plan
other than to stand out

00:34:19.610 --> 00:34:23.080
in the world of theoretical
math and computer science.

00:34:23.080 --> 00:34:26.860
And Akamai was, in
some ways, an accident,

00:34:26.860 --> 00:34:30.620
in the sense of the
business success.

00:34:30.620 --> 00:34:35.010
I mean, if it hadn't happened
at that precise moment,

00:34:35.010 --> 00:34:41.719
and these beautiful ideas
hadn't been given life to

00:34:41.719 --> 00:34:44.791
by this person with
such incredible drive,

00:34:44.791 --> 00:34:46.499
the story would have
been very different.

00:34:49.360 --> 00:34:52.287
So really, to wrap up my
answer to your question,

00:34:52.287 --> 00:34:53.870
I think this really
speaks for itself.

00:34:53.870 --> 00:34:56.620
So Danny became very
rich very quickly.

00:34:56.620 --> 00:34:58.410
He had, obviously,
very little time

00:34:58.410 --> 00:35:01.540
to enjoy it, which is very sad.

00:35:01.540 --> 00:35:04.950
But he didn't want to, really.

00:35:04.950 --> 00:35:08.160
He went out and
bought a couple toys--

00:35:08.160 --> 00:35:10.920
some motorcycles, a new house.

00:35:10.920 --> 00:35:13.000
And then he just really
went back to work.

00:35:13.000 --> 00:35:16.930
And when I asked his colleagues,
what did he want to do?

00:35:16.930 --> 00:35:20.060
What was he going to do
with all that wealth?

00:35:20.060 --> 00:35:22.040
Tom Leighton, who was
still teaching at MIT

00:35:22.040 --> 00:35:24.120
at the time, and his
wife, who was also

00:35:24.120 --> 00:35:27.660
a very successful professor
at MIT and world-renowned,

00:35:27.660 --> 00:35:31.400
said, he wanted
to go back to MIT.

00:35:31.400 --> 00:35:34.970
And before his death, he
enrolled to get his PhD.

00:35:34.970 --> 00:35:37.380
And that was his goal, and
that's what he really wanted.

00:35:37.380 --> 00:35:38.880
And when somebody
said to him, well,

00:35:38.880 --> 00:35:40.380
a PhD will be easy for you.

00:35:40.380 --> 00:35:44.010
Now you can just go back,
write up Akamai's secret sauce,

00:35:44.010 --> 00:35:47.080
and you'll be handed your
PhD on a silver platter.

00:35:47.080 --> 00:35:49.485
So, you know, no problem.

00:35:49.485 --> 00:35:52.110
And he looked at them-- this was
actually Tom Leighton's wife--

00:35:52.110 --> 00:35:54.760
and said, no way.

00:35:54.760 --> 00:35:57.390
I have to find something
so much better.

00:35:57.390 --> 00:35:59.850
I have to do something
totally different.

00:35:59.850 --> 00:36:02.140
I have to change
the world again.

00:36:02.140 --> 00:36:04.020
And that was really his goal.

00:36:04.020 --> 00:36:08.170
And according to everybody,
he was a wonderful teacher.

00:36:08.170 --> 00:36:09.790
And his work at
the whiteboard is

00:36:09.790 --> 00:36:14.270
what won over so many
skeptical businessmen

00:36:14.270 --> 00:36:17.420
and corporate
entrepreneurs at the time

00:36:17.420 --> 00:36:22.207
when Akamai was
first taking off.

00:36:22.207 --> 00:36:23.040
Any other questions?

00:36:29.680 --> 00:36:31.359
Well, thank you again.

00:36:31.359 --> 00:36:33.400
It's an honor again to be
here at Google New York

00:36:33.400 --> 00:36:37.580
to speak to you, and I
hope you enjoy the book.

00:36:37.580 --> 00:36:38.390
Thank you.

